<HEADLINE>
Y2K FACTS &AMP; FIGURES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ The computer industry has known about the Y2K problem since
the early 1980s, but only began working on the problem in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ An estimated 150 million microchips could be problematic.
</P>
<P>
   _ One estimate puts the worldwide cost of correcting the Y2K
problem at $600 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most products bought from 1997 on should be Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Apple Computer's Macintosh is immune to the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   _ To determine if your computer is Y2K compliant, set your
system clock to 11:55 p.m., Dec. 31, 1999. Turn it off and then
back on 15 minutes later. If the date is shown as Jan. 1, 2000,
your system is Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some estimate the Y2K problem will generate $100 billion in
litigation costs alone.
</P>
<P>
   _ As of Nov. 13, 61 percent of the federal government's computer
systems deemed ``mission critical'' had been repaired and tested.
</P>
<P>
   _ Small businesses may be the hardest hit by the Y2K problem.
About 330,000 small businesses may have to close until a technician
is available to solve the problems, and 370,000 others could be
incapacitated.
</P>
